Exchanges Note Plans for Launch
Of E-Based Single Stock Futures Market

CHICAGO--The leaders of Chicago's two futures exchanges and the world's=20
largest options exchange unveiled plans May 14 to launch an electronic=20
single-stock futures exchange.=20
Senior executives of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange Inc., the Chicago Board=
=20
of Trade, and the Chicago Board Options Exchange said they signed a letter o=
f=20
intent to develop the first domestic single-stock futures exchange. The=20
Nasdaq and the London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange=20
announced a single-stock futures venture in March.=20

Ban Lifted on Single-Stock Trading

Plans for the exchange come six months after futures laws were reformed to=20
permit U.S. exchanges to trade single-stock futures. Last December, the=20
Commodity Futures Modernization Act of 2000 was enacted, lifting a=20
prohibition on such transactions for the first time in more than 18 years.=20
During a briefing with reporters, exchange executives said the CME and CBOE=20
would be the two primary partners in the joint venture. Each of the exchange=
s=20
would own 45 percent of the new entity. The CBT would own the remaining 10=20
percent of the exchange. By their coming together in an unusual spirit of=20
cooperation, the exchange officials said, they hoped the as yet unnamed=20
venture would restore Chicago's position as the world leader in futures=20
trading.=20
"This exciting new initiative combines the best of securities and futures=20
trading," said William Brodsky, CBOE chairman and chief executive officer.=20
"Our willingness to work together on this venture will ensure that Chicago=20
remains the world's center in derivatives trading and risk management."=20

Approval of Boards, Regulators Needed

The exchanges said the new entity would be structured as a for-profit compan=
y=20
with its own management and board of directors. The company would be=20
organized separately from the three Chicago exchanges. The proposal still=20
must gain the approval of the boards of directors of the three exchanges and=
=20
federal regulators. Exchange officials said they were still uncertain whethe=
r=20
the Securities and Exchange Commission or the Commodity Futures Trading=20
Commission would be the primary regulator of the new exchange.=20
Exchange officials stressed that the trading activity would be available onl=
y=20
on an electronic basis. Market participants would be able to access the=20
trading via the CME's Globex2 and CBOE's CBOEdirect electronic trading=20
platforms. Exchange officials said they hope to offer principal-to-principal=
=20
trading by Aug. 21 and retail trading by Dec. 21.=20

